    <div class="post-grid">
      <article class="post-content">

        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p>A <strong>carousel ad</strong> is a paid social format that lets users swipe horizontally through 2-10 cards, each with its own image or video, headline, description, and destination URL. It's available on Meta (Facebook + Instagram), LinkedIn, TikTok, and Pinterest, and delivers <strong>up to 10x higher click-through rates</strong> than single-image ads when structured well.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Card count</div>
            <div class="tms-value">2-10 (3-5 optimal)</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Paid Advertising</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">CTR lift (Meta)</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Up to 10x</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Beginner</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">One ad slot, multiple creative angles. Carousel ads let you test five product hooks, five features, or five story beats in the same placement — and the platform auto-picks the winning first card per user. It's the fastest paid format to iterate on because every card is a mini A/B test built into the same buy.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What is a carousel ad?</h2>
        <p>A carousel ad is Meta's original name for a multi-card swipeable paid unit that lets a single ad tell 2-10 stories, sell 2-10 products, or show 2-10 angles of the same object. Each card has its own image or video, its own headline and description, and its own clickable URL.</p>
        <p>Meta launched the format in 2014 as a Facebook feature and quickly extended it to Instagram, Audience Network, and Messenger. LinkedIn added carousel ads in 2019, TikTok in 2022, and Pinterest supports its own variant called <a href="/glossary/carousel-post/">"carousel Pin"</a>.</p>

        <div class="callout callout-info">
          <div class="callout-label">Carousel ad vs carousel post</div>
          <p>A <strong>carousel ad</strong> is a paid placement — it's part of a campaign, has targeting, budget, and reporting. A <strong>carousel post</strong> is organic content that appears in the normal feed. Same swipe UX, entirely different distribution and measurement.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="why-it-matters">Why carousel ads matter</h2>
        <p>Every paid platform is a first-frame game — the visual has to earn the swipe. Carousels win because they get five shots instead of one:</p>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Multiple hooks in one buy.</strong> If card 1 doesn't work, card 2 might. Meta's auto-optimization surfaces the winner per user.</li>
          <li><strong>Higher click-through rates.</strong> Meta reports up to 10x CTR lift versus single-image ads on the same audience.</li>
          <li><strong>Lower cost per acquisition.</strong> Ecommerce brands routinely see 30-50% lower CPA with carousels because the format lets them show product variants without splitting campaigns.</li>
          <li><strong>Built-in storytelling.</strong> Before/after, problem/solution, feature-by-feature — sequence-driven carousels convert cold traffic that single images can't.</li>
          <li><strong>Retargeting-friendly.</strong> Dynamic Product Ads (DPA) use carousels to pull in the exact SKUs a shopper viewed. See <a href="/glossary/dynamic-ads/">dynamic ads</a>.</li>
        </ol>

        <h2 id="how-it-works">How carousel ads work</h2>
        <p>The unit shares a single primary text ("caption") and headline set at the ad level, plus 2-10 individual cards. Each card has:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Media</strong> — 1:1 image (1080×1080px min) or video (1-240 seconds)</li>
          <li><strong>Headline</strong> — up to 40 characters</li>
          <li><strong>Description</strong> — up to 20 characters</li>
          <li><strong>Destination URL</strong> — unique per card, or one shared URL</li>
          <li><strong>CTA button</strong> — from Meta's preset list (Shop Now, Learn More, etc.)</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Meta's default behavior is to <strong>auto-optimize the card order per user</strong>. If your card 4 is the best performer for a given persona, Meta shows it first. To lock a narrative (before/after, story arc), disable auto-optimization at the ad set level.</p>

        <h2 id="types">Carousel ad specs by platform</h2>

        <div class="table-wrap">
