        </div>

        <h2 id="examples">Real carousel ad examples</h2>

        <h3>1. Furniture retailer — 5 sofa variants</h3>
        <p>A DTC furniture brand ran a Meta carousel featuring five modular sofa configurations, each linking to its own product page. Result: <strong>35% lower CPC</strong> than the single-image control ad and 22% higher CTR. Meta's auto-optimization surfaced different lead cards to different personas.</p>
        <div class="url-flow">
          <span class="uf-comment"># Structure that worked</span><br>
          Card 1: <span class="uf-new">Best-selling 3-seat, $1,299</span><br>
          Card 2: <span class="uf-new">Modular corner, $1,899</span><br>
          Card 3: <span class="uf-new">Compact 2-seat, $899</span><br>
          Card 4: <span class="uf-new">Loveseat + ottoman, $1,499</span><br>
          Card 5: <span class="uf-new">"See all 12 configurations" → collection page</span>
        </div>

        <h3>2. B2B SaaS — case-study carousel on LinkedIn</h3>
        <p>A project management SaaS ran a 5-card LinkedIn carousel walking through a customer case study: problem → solution → implementation → result → CTA. Conversion rate on the lead form: <strong>4.2%</strong>, roughly double the CTR of static single-image ads targeting the same audience.</p>

        <h3>3. Retargeting with Dynamic Product Ads (DPA)</h3>
        <p>An apparel brand connected its product catalog to Meta and served automatic carousels of the last 4-8 items each shopper viewed. Meta pulled the SKUs, images, and prices dynamically — the marketer never built a manual creative. ROAS on cold audiences: 2.1x. ROAS on the DPA retargeting carousel: <strong>6.4x</strong>.</p>

        <h2 id="vs-related">Carousel ad vs single-image ad — when to pick which</h2>
        <p>Both formats can win. Choose based on how many story beats or products the campaign needs.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Use a carousel ad when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>You have 3+ products or features to show</li>
              <li>The story has a sequence (before/after, steps)</li>
              <li>You want automatic card testing baked in</li>
              <li>You're running dynamic product retargeting</li>
              <li>Cold audiences need multiple hooks</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Use a single-image or video ad when</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>The offer is one product, one hook</li>
              <li>You're chasing a single conversion event</li>
              <li>Creative bandwidth is limited</li>
              <li>The audience is warm and pre-sold</li>
              <li>You need maximum first-frame simplicity</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="best-practices">7 carousel ad best practices</h2>
        <ol>
          <li><strong>Lead with the strongest card.</strong> Even with auto-optimization on, the seed card 1 shapes early performance. Put your best creative first.</li>
          <li><strong>Use 3-5 cards for most objectives.</strong> Ecommerce catalogs can extend to 10. More cards for storytelling rarely help — swipe fatigue is real.</li>
          <li><strong>Match media type to the audience.</strong> Video cards outperform static images 60-80% of the time. Mix video + image if you must, but never lead with static.</li>
          <li><strong>Write card-level headlines, not repeat text.</strong> Each card headline should stand alone as a benefit or hook. Repeating your brand name across 5 cards is wasted space.</li>
          <li><strong>Use one primary text, distinct per-card headlines.</strong> The primary text should introduce the theme. Card headlines carry the specifics.</li>
          <li><strong>Enable auto-optimization by default.</strong> Unless the sequence is narrative (before/after, story arc), let Meta pick the best card 1 per user.</li>
          <li><strong>Track card-level CTR.</strong> In Ads Manager, break down by "Card" to see which cards drive the outcome. Kill the losers, iterate on the winners.</li>
        </ol>

        <div class="callout callout-warn">
          <div class="callout-label">Common trap — text-heavy card overlays</div>
          <p>Meta no longer enforces the old 20%-text rule, but text-heavy overlays still get lower CTR and higher CPMs. Keep on-image text to a single benefit line and let the primary text carry the message. Cluttered cards perform worst on the first-frame test.</p>
        </div>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common carousel ad mistakes to avoid</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Same image with different colors on every card</strong> — Meta's algorithm treats it as low-variance and CTR collapses.</li>
          <li><strong>Locking the card order without a narrative reason</strong> — you lose the auto-optimization lift.</li>
          <li><strong>Sending every card to the same URL</strong> — kills the reason to swipe. Use unique destinations per card whenever possible.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring card-level reporting</strong> — the whole point of carousels is per-card learning.</li>
          <li><strong>Overlong videos on card 1</strong> — first-card video should hook in 3-5 seconds; save longer content for later cards.</li>
          <li><strong>Skipping the final "collection" card</strong> — ecommerce carousels lift ROAS when the last card links to a "shop all" collection page.</li>
        </ul>

